      <description>&lt;div class="hs-featured-image-wrapper"&gt; 
 &lt;a href="https://blog.avast.com/newest-data-privacy-legislation" title="" class="hs-featured-image-link"&gt; &lt;img src="https://blog.avast.com/hubfs/privacy-legislation.jpg" alt="Newest State Data Privacy Legislation | Avast" class="hs-featured-image" style="width:auto !important; max-width:50%; float:left; margin:0 15px 15px 0;"&gt; &lt;/a&gt; 
&lt;/div&gt; 
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #222222;"&gt;When we wrote about &lt;/span&gt;&lt;a href="https://blog.avast.com/2022-data-privacy-legislation-update-avast"&gt;&lt;span&gt;state privacy laws&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="color: #222222;"&gt; earlier this year, Virginia, California, and Colorado were the only states with laws in place to protect consumers’ privacy. (&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.onetrust.com/blog/the-nevada-privacy-law-sb-220-vs-the-california-consumer-privacy-act-ccpa/"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Nevada has also had a more limited law since 2019&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="color: #222222;"&gt;.) Since then, &lt;/span&gt;Utah Governor Spencer Cox signed the Utah Consumer Privacy Act (&lt;a href="https://le.utah.gov/~2022/bills/static/SB0227.html" style="color: #0846c2;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;SB 227&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;) on March 24, 2022, and Virginia has enacted three additional laws amending its &lt;a href="https://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?211+sum+SB1392"&gt;Consumer Data Protection Act&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded>&lt;div class="hs-featured-image-wrapper"&gt; 
 &lt;a href="https://blog.avast.com/newest-data-privacy-legislation" title="" class="hs-featured-image-link"&gt; &lt;img src="https://blog.avast.com/hubfs/privacy-legislation.jpg" alt="Newest State Data Privacy Legislation | Avast" class="hs-featured-image" style="width:auto !important; max-width:50%; float:left; margin:0 15px 15px 0;"&gt; &lt;/a&gt; 
&lt;/div&gt; 
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #222222;"&gt;When we wrote about &lt;/span&gt;&lt;a href="https://blog.avast.com/2022-data-privacy-legislation-update-avast"&gt;&lt;span&gt;state privacy laws&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="color: #222222;"&gt; earlier this year, Virginia, California, and Colorado were the only states with laws in place to protect consumers’ privacy. (&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.onetrust.com/blog/the-nevada-privacy-law-sb-220-vs-the-california-consumer-privacy-act-ccpa/"&gt;&lt;span&gt;Nevada has also had a more limited law since 2019&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="color: #222222;"&gt;.) Since then, &lt;/span&gt;Utah Governor Spencer Cox signed the Utah Consumer Privacy Act (&lt;a href="https://le.utah.gov/~2022/bills/static/SB0227.html" style="color: #0846c2;"&gt;&lt;span&gt;SB 227&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;) on March 24, 2022, and Virginia has enacted three additional laws amending its &lt;a href="https://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?211+sum+SB1392"&gt;Consumer Data Protection Act&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;  
